reason.tex:
%text
By definition $\dfrac{d^2y}{dx^2} = \dfrac{d}{dx}\left( \dfrac{dy}{dx}\right)$.  However,
this also means that 
%
\begin{align}
\dfrac{d^2 y}{dx^2} &= \underbrace{\dfrac{d}{dt}\left(\dfrac{dy}{dx}\right)\times
\dfrac{dt}{dx}}_{ = \dfrac{d}{dx}\dfrac{dy}{dx}}
\end{align} 

%text

Hence, when $x=t^2$ and $y=t^3$, then 
%
\begin{align}
\dfrac{dx}{dt} &= 2t \implies\dfrac{dt}{dx} = \dfrac{1}{2t} \\
\dfrac{dy}{dx} &= 3t^2 \\
\dfrac{dy}{dx} &= \dfrac{\left( \dfrac{dy}{dt}\right)}{\left( \dfrac{dx}{dt}\right)}
= \dfrac{3t^2}{2t} = \dfrac{3t}{2} \\
\dfrac{d^2 y}{dx^2} &= \dfrac{d}{dt}\left(\dfrac{dy}{dx}\right)\cdot\dfrac{dt}{dx}
= \left(\dfrac{d}{dt}\dfrac{3t}{2}\right)\cdot\dfrac{1}{2t} = \dfrac{3}{4t}
\end{align} 

%text

Compare this with $ \dfrac{\left( \dfrac{d^2 y}{dt^2}\right)}{\left( \dfrac{d^2 x}{dt^2}\right)}$.
%
\begin{align}
\dfrac{dx}{dt} &= 2t \implies \dfrac{d^2 x}{dt^2} = 2 \\
\dfrac{dy}{dt} &= 3t^2 \implies \dfrac{d^2 y}{dt^2} = 6t \\
\dfrac{\left( \dfrac{d^2 y}{dt^2}\right)}{\left( \dfrac{d^2 x}{dt^2}\right)}
&= \dfrac{6t}{2} = 3t \neq 
\underbrace{\dfrac{3}{4t}}_{= \frac{d^2y}{dx^2}}
\end{align}

\begin{align}
\frac{dy}{dx} &= \cot t \\
\therefore \frac{d^2 y}{dx^2} &= \frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{dy}{dx}\right)\cdot\frac{dt}{dx}
= \frac{d}{dt}\cot t\cdot\frac{1}{a\cdot\cos t} \\
&= \frac{-\csc^2 t}{a\cdot \cos t} = \underbrace{-\frac{2}{a\cdot 2\sin^2 t\cdot\cos t}}
_{\text{Multiply and divide by 2}} \\
&= -\dfrac{2}{a\cdot\sin t\cdot (2\sin t\cdot \cos t)} \\ 
&= -\dfrac{2}{a\cdot\sin t\cdot \sin 2t}
\end{align}
